    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "J o u r n a l P r e -p r o o f",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": ""
        },
        {
            "text": "Epilepsy is a chronic neurological disorder that causes recurrent, unprovoked seizures. It is known that 20-30% of patients with epilepsy experience symptoms of depression [1] . Compared to healthy people, patients with epilepsy have a 40-50% higher suicide rate [2] .",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 172,
                    "end": 175,
                    "text": "[1]",
                    "ref_id": null
                },
                {
                    "start": 263,
                    "end": 266,
                    "text": "[2]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF2"
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "text": "Coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) initially occurred in Wuhan, China in late 2019 before its global outbreak [3] . It is a novel infectious disease caused by severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2). The COVID-19 crisis has been stressful for people across the world, with everyone having to adapt to the changes involved.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 111,
                    "end": 114,
                    "text": "[3]",
                    "ref_id": null
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "text": "It is important for clinicians to consider the psychological impact of this crisis while treating patients with epilepsy. Firstly, we have discussed how epilepsy causes mental stress in patients. (Fig.1 ) We have also considered how the COVID-19 crisis affects the mental health of patients with epilepsy. (Fig.2) ",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 196,
                    "end": 202,
                    "text": "(Fig.1",
                    "ref_id": "FIGREF1"
                },
                {
                    "start": 306,
                    "end": 313,
                    "text": "(Fig.2)",
                    "ref_id": "FIGREF2"
                }
            ],
            "section": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "text": "J o u r n a l P r e -p r o o f 4 Kuroda on seizures, physicians treating epilepsy need to be aware of the patient's original mental state and premorbid personality. The patient also needs to be evaluated for any changes.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Mental changes associated with seizures"
        },
        {
            "text": "Psychiatric symptoms may occur as a symptom of the seizure itself and are known to be more common in temporal lobe epilepsy [4] . As these are seizure symptoms that occur during the duration of the seizure, the quality of life of the patient may be affected because of the fear of the onset of the mood symptoms.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 124,
                    "end": 127,
                    "text": "[4]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF5"
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Mental changes associated with seizures"
        },
        {
            "text": "The psychiatric symptoms that accompany the end of a seizure are known as postictal psychiatric disturbances or postictal mood disorders and commonly occur after frequent seizures and generalized seizures. There is typically an asymptomatic period spanning hours or days after the seizure, followed by a rapid hallucinatory delirium along with aggression and exaggeration [4] . Basically, it improves within a week with selfremitting. In contrast, postictal depression is less recognized in psychiatric practice as compared to postictal psychoses. However, these are frequently reported by patients and relatives [4] . Its symptoms, including dysphoria and crying bout, are characteristics of J o u r n a l P r e -p r o o f Kuroda ",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 372,
                    "end": 375,
                    "text": "[4]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF5"
                },
                {
                    "start": 613,
                    "end": 616,
                    "text": "[4]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF5"
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Mental changes associated with seizures"
        }
